Understanding the Results:
Unsupervised Learning: 
Notice we didn't give the model "correct answers" (labels). It found the groups on its own based solely on the distance between points.
The Centroid: Each cluster is defined by its center point. In the output, the centroid [5233.33, 22.33] represents the "average" VIP customer.
Choosing K: In this example, we chose $k=3$. In real-world scenarios, you would often use the Elbow Method to determine the optimal number of clusters by plotting the variance against the number of clusters.
Sensitivity: K-Means can be sensitive to outliers and the initial placement of centroids, which is why it often runs multiple times (defined by n_init) to find the best grouping.
